<F P=100> NORTHEAST ASIA </F>
<F P=101> Japan </F>
<H3> <TI>   EPA Chief Pledges Stimulus Steps by Mid-Jan </TI></H3>
<F P=102>  OW1101031794 Tokyo KYODO in English 0155 GMT 11 Jan 94 </F>
<F P=103> OW1101031794 </F>
<F P=104>  Tokyo KYODO </F>


<TEXT>
Language: <F P=105> English </F>
Article Type:BFN 

  [Text] Tokyo, Jan. 11 KYODO -- The Economic Planning 
Agency (EPA) will do its utmost to formulate a new set of 
pump-priming measures by mid-January, the agency chief said 
Tuesday [11 January]. 
  The ruling coalition parties are working hard to iron out 
their difference on whether to hike the consumption tax to 
finance an income tax cut, EPA Director General Manae Kubota 
told a regular press conference. 
  When a consensus is reached on this "thorny issue," Kubota 
said, the ruling coalition parties will coordinate their view 
with the government at a joint economic forum. 
  The Social Democratic Party [of Japan], the largest in the 
seven-party coalition, has been strongly opposed to hiking the 
consumption tax. 

</TEXT>

</DOC>

