<F P=100> NORTHEAST ASIA </F>
<F P=101> Japan </F>
<H3> <TI>   Farm Minister Urges Lower Price for Imported Rice </TI></H3>
<F P=102>  OW1101053994 Tokyo KYODO in English 0528 GMT 11 Jan 94 </F>
<F P=103> OW1101053994 </F>
<F P=104>  Tokyo KYODO </F>


<TEXT>
Language: <F P=105> English </F>
Article Type:BFN 

  [Text] Tokyo, Jan. 11 KYODO -- Japan's farm minister 
recommends that imported long-grain rice for table use from 
Thailand should be retailed at half the price of domestic rice, 
ministry officials said Tuesday [11 January]. 
  Eijiro Hata, minister of agriculture, forestry and 
fisheries, 
said at a meeting of cabinet ministers that the retail price of 
rice from California should be 70 percent of the standard price 
of Japanese rice and rice from China should be sold at 60 
percent of the ordinary domestic rice price. 
  Japan is importing rice on emergency basis in the current 
fiscal year due to a bad crop in 1993. 
  In the meeting, Manae Kubota, director general of the 
Economic Planning Agency said, retail price-setting should be 
consumer-oriented and the government should advise retailers to 
show the year of production of the rice they are selling. 
  A committee meeting of the Rice Price Council will be held 
Thursday to discuss the retail prices of such imported rice. 
  Kubota called on Hata to ensure that the price for rice to 
be 
imported from next fiscal year beginning in April under the 
government's minimum access policy should be set at a council 
meeting before the government officially decides the price, 
ministry sources said. 
  Japan has decided to partially open its rice market under an 
agreement in the Uruguay round trade talks which were wrapped up 
in December. 

</TEXT>

</DOC>

