<F P=100> NORTHEAST ASIA </F>
<F P=101> Japan </F>
<H3> <TI>   Defense Chief, Hosokawa To Review Defense Plan </TI></H3>
<F P=102>  OW1101072094 Tokyo KYODO in English 0659 GMT 11 Jan 94 </F>
<F P=103> OW1101072094 </F>
<F P=104>  Tokyo KYODO </F>


<TEXT>
Language: <F P=105> English </F>
Article Type:BFN 

  [Text] Tokyo, Jan. 11 KYODO -- Defense Agency chief Kazuo 
Aichi said Tuesday [11 January] he will consult with Prime 
Minister Morihiro Hosokawa to review Japan's national defense 
program outline. 
  Aichi, director general of the agency, made the remark to 
reporters after a cabinet meeting on the issue. 
  "I will consult with Prime Minister Hosokawa on arranging 
the 
reviews. We must go ahead with the work within the 
understanding of one another on the issue," he said. He 
admitted that relations between the prime minister and the 
agency on the issue were insufficient. 
  The prime minister has voiced his intention to set up his 
advisory panel to review the defense program outline and to 
reach a conclusion by around summer. 
  But some Defense Agency officials have opposed Hosokawa's 
proposal. 
  Aichi hinted at a meeting with Hosokawa in February after 
political reform bills are enacted. The bills are expected to 
pass through the Diet by the end of the current Diet session on 
January 29. 
  The cabinet of Former Prime Minister Takeo Miki drafted the 
defense plan in 1976, which outlines the need to arrange armed 
forces through numerical targets. 
  Since then the agency has drafted midterm, five-year defense 
buildup programs based on the outline. 
  Japan has considered reviewing the defense outline since the 
Soviet Union collapsed in 1991. 

</TEXT>

