<F P=100> SOUTHEAST ASIA </F>
<F P=101> Cambodia </F>
<H3> <TI>   Sar Kheng Receives U.S. Congressional Delegation </TI></H3>
<F P=102>  BK1101071194 Phnom Penh AKP in French 0404 GMT 11 Jan 94 </F>
<F P=103> BK1101071194 </F>
<F P=104>  Phnom Penh AKP </F>


<TEXT>
Language: <F P=105> French </F>
Article Type:BFN 

  [Text] Phnom Penh 11 Jan (AKP) -- The prevention of 
hostile activities by the Khmer Rouge is a duty of the Royal 
Government of Cambodia [RGC], but it is also a commitment of the 
international community. This was emphasized by Sar Kheng, 
deputy prime minister and co-interior minister, at a meeting on 
Sunday, 9 January, with a U.S. congressional delegation led by 
Mr. Wilson of the Foreign Relations Commission. 
  Mr. Sar Kheng briefed his guests about the recent 
appointment 
of provincial governors, the new administrative structures 
organized in line with the principle of national reconciliation 
and unity, and the mutual understanding between major political 
parties elected to the National Assembly under the 
clear-sightedness of His Majesty Norodom Sihanouk. 
  For his part, Mr. Wilson commended the close cooperation 
between the Cambodian People's Party and the FUNCINPEC [National 
United Front for an Independent, Neutral, Peaceful, and 
Cooperative Cambodia] Party. The United States, he added, is 
delighted to see respect for human rights and for the Kingdom of 
Cambodia's Constitution. 
  The U.S. senator expressed his confidence that the RGC would 
be able to defend security and bring about peace for the 
Cambodian people. 
  Mr. Charles Twining, U.S. ambassador to Cambodia was also 
present at the audience. 

</TEXT>

