<F P=100> South Korea </F>
<H3> <TI>   Report Shows Little Foreign Investment in DPRK </TI></H3>
<F P=102>  SK1101033994 Seoul MAEIL KYONGJE SINMUN in Korean 11 Jan 94 
p 2 </F>

<F P=103> SK1101033994 </F>
<F P=104>  Seoul MAEIL KYONGJE SINMUN </F>


<TEXT>
Language: <F P=105> Korean </F>
Article Type:BFN 

  [Text] It has been learned that even though North Korea 
enacted laws aimed at attracting foreign capital in 1992, 
including a law guaranteeing foreign investment, only three 
joint-venture businesses have been set up in North Korea. 
  In addition, the number of joint-venture companies doing 
business in North Korea has diminished from 120 to 20, Yi 
Yong-tok, deputy premier and national unification minister, said 
on 10 January in a report to the National Assembly Foreign 
Affairs-Unification Committee. 
  According to the report, the three joint-venture companies 
that were established in the last year are Aeguk Adhesion Plant, 
Aeguk Color Television Assembly Plant, and Myongsim 
Joint-Venture Company manufacturing graphite, which are all 
jointly invested with Japanese companies. 
  The report revealed that there is a great possibility that 
North Korea has transferred initiative for economic policies 
from the Workers' Party of North Korea to the Administration 
Council as part of a policy attaching great importance to 
professionalism rather than partisanship. 

</TEXT>

</DOC>

