<F P=100> South Korea </F>
<H3> <TI>   More Aid Pledged for UN Commission on Refugees </TI></H3>
<F P=102>  SK1001034794 Seoul YONHAP in English 0259 GMT 10 Jan 94 </F>
<F P=103> SK1001034794 </F>
<F P=104>  Seoul YONHAP </F>


<TEXT>
Language: <F P=105> English </F>
Article Type:BFN 

  [Text] Seoul, Jan. 10 (YONHAP) -- South Korean Foreign 
Minister Han Sung-chu pledged more voluntary contributions to UN 
aid for refugees in addition to manpower donations Monday. 
  Han promised visiting UN High Commissioner for Refugees 
Sadako Ogata wider assistance for the commission, said Ham 
Myong-chol, director-general of international organizations. 
  Seoul's contribution to the United Nations as a member state 
accounts for 0.69 percent of the U.N. budget, but its voluntary 
donations to other international bodies such as the commission 
is 0.04 percent. 
  Korea gave 150,000 U.S. dollars to the commission last year, 
when it joined the convention on better protection and welfare 
of the refugees. This ranks 28th among the 48 contributor 
nations. 
  While increasing the amount of monetary donations, Han said, 
the government could send medical and other emergency aid teams 
to troubled areas. 
  These teams may be sent as part of youth volunteer programs 
at the Korea International Cooperation Agency (KOICA), a Foreign 
Ministry umbrella institution, he said. 

</TEXT>

</DOC>

