<F P=100> South Korea </F>
<H3> <TI>   Seoul To Sign Investment Protection Pacts </TI></H3>
<F P=102>  SK1101003494 Seoul THE KOREA TIMES in English 11 Jan 94 p 2 </F>
<F P=103> SK1101003494 </F>
<F P=104>  Seoul THE KOREA TIMES </F>


<TEXT>
Language: <F P=105> English </F>
Article Type:BFN 

  [Text] The government plans to conclude investment 
protection agreements with 10 developing nations this year to 
help domestic companies invest more easily in the countries, 
Foreign Ministry officials said yesterday [10 January]. 
  The nations involved are India, Hong Kong, Papua New Guinea, 
Mexico, Argentina, Chile, Panama, Egypt, Algeria and Kazakhstan. 
  An official said that the countries are expected to attract 
more investment from Korean companies. As of the end of last 
June, Korean firms had invested an estimated $365 million in the 
10 countries. 
  Domestic companies are expected to be active in investment 
in 
India in the wake of Indian Prime Minister Narasimha Rao's visit 
to Seoul last September, the official said. 
  With Hong Kong, Korea should take action after 1997 when the 
island state will be handed over to China, he said, adding that 
there has been no investment pact signed by the two sides 
although Korea and China concluded a similar pact last year. 
  Mexico is important as it is a member of the three-nation 
North American Free Trade Agreement (NAFTA) put into effect Jan. 
1 this year. Mexico without investment guarantee pacts with 
foreign countries due to a constitutional ban is seeking such 
pacts to attract foreign investment, he said. 
  The agreement with Argentina will be signed soon as 
obstacles 
have been brushed away, the official said. The government is 
also seeking an agreement with Kazakhstan as domestic companies 
are eager to invest in the country which has a large number of 
ethnic Koreans. 
  Korea has concluded investment protection pacts with 24 
countries and initialed them with eight. 

</TEXT>

</DOC>

