<F P=100> South Korea </F>
<H3> <TI>   Annual Exports of Top Business Groups Reported </TI></H3>
<F P=102>  SK1101064894 Seoul YONHAP in English 0527 GMT 11 Jan 94 </F>
<F P=103> SK1101064894 </F>
<F P=104>  Seoul YONHAP </F>


<TEXT>
Language: <F P=105> English </F>
Article Type:BFN 

  [Text] Seoul, Jan. 11 (YONHAP) -- Korea's 10 largest 
business groups had exports of 47.32 billion U.S. dollars last 
year, or 57.4 percent of total exports, the Trade, Industry and 
Energy Ministry said Tuesday. 
  Samsung, Hyundai, Lucky-Goldstar and Daewoo accounted for 
40.2 percent of Korea's total exports of 82.44 billion dollars. 
  Samsung ranked first with 12.7 percent of exports, up from 
11.2 percent a year earlier. 
  Hyundai ranked second with 8.3 billion dollars, off 370 
million dollars because of labor disputes at 10 percent, down 
from 11.3 percent. Hyundai led Samsung last year at 8.67 
billion dollars to 8.6 billion dollars. 
  Lucky-Goldstar was stable in third place at 7.7 billion 
dollars, or 9.3 percent of exports compared with 9.2 percent in 
1992. 
  Daewoo followed at 6.8 billion dollars (8.2 percent), Hanjin 
at 4.81 billion dollars (5.8 percent), Sunkyong at 4.48 billion 
dollars (5.4 percent), Ssangyong at 2.6 billion dollars (3.1 
percent) and Kia at 1.1 billion dollars (1.3 percent). 
  The Hyosung Group had 2.64 billion dollars in exports, or 
3.2 
percent, for sixth place, but is not among the 10 biggest groups. 
  Hanwha and Lotte ranked ninth and tenth at 0.7 percent and 
0.4 percent, respectively. 
  Ssangyong slipped from 3.2 percent to 3.1 percent, but the 
rest improved their figures. 

</TEXT>

