<F P=100> South Korea </F>
<H3> <TI>   Employers Group Expects Early End to Wage Talks </TI></H3>
<F P=102>  SK1101012494 Seoul YONHAP in English 0110 GMT 11 Jan 94 </F>
<F P=103> SK1101012494 </F>
<F P=104>  Seoul YONHAP </F>


<TEXT>
Language: <F P=105> English </F>
Article Type:BFN 

  [Text] Seoul, Jan. 11 (YONHAP) -- Wage negotiations are 
expected to be completed earlier than in previous years, Korea 
Employers' Association (KEA) Vice Chairman Hwang Chong-hyon 
forecast Tuesday [11 January]. 
  KEA wants to complete its talks with the Federation of 
Korean 
Trade Unions (FKTU) by the middle of February and finish company 
talks before the end of March, Hwang said. 
  "As the government has set this year's goal at strengthening 
international competitiveness of the nation and has a strong 
will to control prices, price hikes will not be so considerable 
a reason for wage increases," he predicted. 
  Economic Planning Minister Chong Chae-sok and Labor Minister 
Nam Chae-hui told FKTU Chairman Pak Chong-kon on Saturday [8 
January] that the government intends to control prices, and Pak 
said FKTU will seek to end its wage negotiations with KEA as 
early as possible if prices are controlled. 
  KEA will draw up wage demands by the middle of this month 
and 
select negotiators to meet with FKTU late this month. 
  "Government, management and labor met in October and agreed 
to change ties between management and labor to autonomous and 
cooperative," an FKTU spokesman said. "Moreover, workers share 
the view that increasing competitiveness is the only way for 
Korea to survive in a competitive international arena." 
  KEA and FKTU agreed on a unified wage hike plan in April for 
the first time. 

</TEXT>

</DOC>

