<F P=100> South Korea </F>
<H3> <TI>   Defense Sets Up New Logistics Programs Committee </TI></H3>
<F P=102>  SK0801004294 Seoul YONHAP in English 1113 GMT 7 Jan 94 </F>
<F P=103> SK0801004294 </F>
<F P=104>  Seoul YONHAP </F>


<TEXT>
Language: <F P=105> English </F>
Article Type:BFN 

  [Text] Seoul, Jan. 7 (YONHAP) -- The National Defense 
Ministry reported on Friday it had established a defense system 
improvement committee to work out ways to improve military arms 
procurement system so as to prevent the recurrence of incidents 
similar to the recent arms procurement scam. 
  Lt. Gen. Chang Song, superintendent of the military academy, 
was named to head the committee, a ministry official said. 
  The committee, to go into operation on Jan. 10, will have 
two 
subcommittees -- one on the improvement of the Yulgok project 
and the other on the improvement of military supply procurement 
system. 
  The former will be chaired by Maj. Gen. Kil Hyong-bo and the 
latter by Brig. Gen. Yu Song-u. 
  Defense Minister Yi Byong-tae, naming Lt. Gen. Chang as 
committee chairman, told him to oversee committee business on a 
full-time basis, leaving military academy duties to the cadet 
corps commander, the official said. 
  The committee will be operated through the end of February 
and its membership number 15 -- eight for the Yulgok project 
subcommittee and seven for the supply procurement one. 
  Members have been picked up from among logistics experts at 
the ministry, Joint Chiefs of Staff, tri-service headquarters 
and defense institutes, the official added. 

</TEXT>

