<F P=100> South Korea </F>
<H3> <TI>   EPB Plans Unit To Screen Yulgok Projects Budget </TI></H3>
<F P=102>  SK1001005794 Seoul YONHAP in English 0020 GMT 10 Jan 94 </F>
<F P=103> SK1001005794 </F>
<F P=104>  Seoul YONHAP </F>


<TEXT>
Language: <F P=105> English </F>
Article Type:BFN 

  [Text] Seoul, Jan. 10 (YONHAP) -- The government plans to 
form a section, or a bureau, in the Economic Planning Board 
(EPB) to take charge of budgeting for the Yulgok military 
buildup program. 
  The plan is part of moves by the government to practically 
screen each and every military project before it decides the 
defense budget, EPB officials said Monday. 
  The decision was apparently prompted by suspected 
irregularities in the Yulgok project and a recent artillery 
ammunition scandal. Public criticisms have been rising against 
the misuses of taxpayers' money under the pretext of military 
buildup. 
  In the past, the Defense Ministry asked for an annual budget 
for the Yulgok projects without specifying in detail where it 
was going to use the money. Because of the nature of the 
projects, the military has maintained that they had to be kept 
in secret. 
  From now on, however, all Yulgok projects are to be subject 
to screening by budget compilers at the EPB, who will check the 
need and soundness of each project. The Yulgok projects had 
accounted for 30 percent to 40 percent of the total defense 
spending every year. 
  The Yulgok project, which was launched by President Pak 
Chong-hui in 1974, had spent a total of 30 trillion won. Last 
year's budget for the project amounted to 2.9 trillion won, or 
31.6 percent of the entire national defense budget. 
  There are 148 projects, including the purchase of the Air 
Force's next generation fighter plane and new tanks for the Army 
and destroyers and submarines for the Navy. 

</TEXT>

</DOC>

<DOC>
<DOCNO> FBIS3-47260 </DOCNO>
<HT>    "dreas007_d_94026" </HT>


