<F P=100> Vietnam </F>
<H3> <TI>   Commentary: Clinton Must `Solve' Embargo Issue </TI></H3>
<F P=102>  BK1101133394 Hanoi Voice of Vietnam in English 1000 GMT 11 
Jan 94 </F>

<F P=103> BK1101133394 </F>
<F P=104>  Hanoi Voice of Vietnam </F>


<TEXT>
Language: <F P=105> English </F>
Article Type:BFN 

<F P=106> [Station commentary] </F>
  [Text] Six delegations of the United State Congress and 
large American companies are expected in Vietnam during the 
first two weeks of January. Currently, a delegation of the U.S. 
Senate Energy and Natural Resources Commission [as heard] is in 
Hanoi. Here is our radio editor's opinion: 
  From now to the middle of January, five United States 
delegations will come to Vietnam. They will represent large 
United States companies such as IBM and General Motors, and 
include the delegation of the Defense Subcommittee of the United 
States Senate, a delegation of the Asia-Pacific Subcommittee of 
the U.S. House of Representatives led by Russell Wilson, a 
delegation under Senator John Kerry, and a delegation led by 
Admiral Charles Larson, commander-in-chief of the U.S. 
Asia-Pacific command. 
  According to Western news agencies, the delegations will 
visit Vietnam to find out possibilities of cooperation and for a 
precise assessment of the renovation process in Vietnam. 
Through their visits, they expect to make a recommendation to 
President Clinton to remove the 20-year-long economic embargo 
against Vietnam. 
  United States Senator Bennett Johnston, head of a delegation 
from the U.S. Senate Energy and Natural Resources Commission, 
last Saturday [8 January] called on the United States President 
to remove the embargo. He said in Hanoi that it was time to 
close the door on the past and move toward normalizing of 
relations and cooperation. Speaking to a REUTERS correspondent 
in Hanoi, he hoped the U.S. President would quickly remove the 
sanction against Vietnam. 
  Senator Don Nickles, a Republican Party member of the same 
delegation, also said he wants the United States President to 
lift the embargo. 
  The voice of the United States politicians demanding the 
lifting of the embargo will become stronger in 1994. The 
American delegations to visit Vietnam in the coming days will 
surely have the same voice as the delegation of Senator Johnston. 
  It is an issue President Clinton has to consider and solve. 

</TEXT>

