<F P=100> North Korea </F>
<H3> <TI>   Statement `Exposing' Anti-DPRK `Moves' Reported </TI></H3>
<F P=102>  SK0801103494 Pyongyang KCNA in English 1015 GMT 8 Jan 94 </F>
<F P=103> SK0801103494 </F>
<F P=104>  Pyongyang KCNA </F>


<TEXT>
Language: <F P=105> English </F>
Article Type:BFN 

  [Text] Pyongyang, January 8 (KCNA) -- Robert Charvin, 
secretary general of the International Committee of Jurists for 
Democracy and Human Rights in South Korea, on December 22, 1993, 
issued a written statement exposing the United States and South 
Korean authorities' anti-DPRK, anti-popular moves and 
distributed it to UN nongovernmental and other international 
organizations. 
  The statement charged that the United States was kicking up 
a 
nuclear racket on the pretext of North Korea's "nuclear threat" 
with a view to justifying its acts of interference against Asia. 
  The Seoul "civilian government", it said, defined North 
Korea 
as "a danger" and has brought even the North-South dialogue to a 
deadlock, still following the methods employed by the former 
military dictatorial "regime", to continually intensify 
crackdown on the South Korean people. 
  The statement noted that the South Korean authorities, 
ignoring the righteous aspirations of South Korean students, 
have been ruthlessly trampling upon even the elementary human 
rights of the people and opened the rice market to jeopardize 
the existence of peasants. 
  It referred to the South Korean authorities' failure to urge 
Japan to pay compensations for the "comfort women for the Army". 

</TEXT>

