<F P=100> North Korea </F>
<H3> <TI>   Indonesia's Suharto on Solving Nuclear Question </TI></H3>
<F P=102>  SK0801101694 Pyongyang KCNA in English 1002 GMT 8 Jan 93 </F>
<F P=103> SK0801101694 </F>
<F P=104>  Pyongyang KCNA </F>


<TEXT>
Language: <F P=105> English </F>
Article Type:BFN 

  [Text] Pyongyang, January 8 (KCNA) -- Indonesian President 
Suharto urged all parties concerned to sincerely contribute to 
creating the needed circumstances for talks on the solution of 
the nuclear issue on the Korean peninsula. 
  In a statement on the nuclear issue of the Korean peninsula 
he issued on January 5 in the name of the chairman of the 
Non-Aligned Movement [NAM], he recalled that heads of state and 
government of all member nations of the NAM, at the 10th summit 
conference of the non-aligned nations, had discussed the 
affirmative development for the peaceful reunification of Korea 
and realization of the joint declaration on the denuclearisation 
of the Korean peninsula and expressed support for them. 
  The president said that Indonesia, as the chairman-state of 
the NAM, had got a series of measures taken to create a climate 
favorable to a peaceful solution of the nuclear issue. 
Indonesia is firmly convinced that the Democratic People's 
Republic of Korea, a member of the NAM, is intending to solve 
the nuclear problem through negotiations, he said, and added: It 
welcomes the will of all parties concerned to solve the nuclear 
problem through negotiations. 

</TEXT>

