<F P=100> South Korea </F>
<H3> <TI>   YONHAP Reports on Visit of Senators Nunn, Lugar </TI></H3>
<H4>   Meet With President Kim </H4>
<F P=102> SK1101021794 Seoul YONHAP in English 0210 GMT 11 Jan 94 </F>
<F P=103> SK1101021794 </F>
<F P=104>  Seoul YONHAP </F>


<TEXT>
Language: <F P=105> English </F>
Article Type:BFN 

  [Text] Seoul, Jan. 11 (YONHAP) -- President Kim Yong-sam 
stressed Tuesday [11 January] closest South Korea-U.S. 
cooperation and understanding now on the North Korean nuclear 
problem while repeating that the problem has to be solved for 
Korean and regional peace. 
  Kim met with visiting American senators Sam Nunn and Richard 
Lugar over breakfast and requested continued support from the 
U.S. Congress for such cooperation, Spokesman Chu Ton-sik said. 
  Nunn, chairman of the Senate Armed Services Committee, and 
his entourage came to Seoul after visiting Russia on what 
officials here called a field trip. 
  The spokesman said there was no discussion of sanctions on 
North Korea in case diplomatic dialogue fails but described the 
senators visit as intended to gather necessary information on 
various possibilities if sanctions become inevitable. 
  Nunn reaffirmed the U.S. security commitment to Seoul, 
recalling President Bill Clinton's words that an attack on South 
Korea is an attack on the United States. This, he said, was the 
position of the United States. 
  He called South Korea-U.S. cooperation an invaluable 
prerequisite to stability on the Korean peninsula and added that 
American troops need to stay in South Korea, the spokesman said. 
  The senators return to Washington later Tuesday. 

</TEXT>

