<F P=100> Laos </F>
<H3> <TI>   President Receives New U.S. Ambassador </TI></H3>
<F P=102>  BK1001094494 Vientiane KPL in English 0805 GMT 10 Jan 94 </F>
<F P=103> BK1001094494 </F>
<F P=104>  Vientiane KPL </F>


<TEXT>
Language: <F P=105> English </F>
Article Type:BFN 

  [Text] Vientiane, January 10 (KPL) -- Nouhak Phoumsavan, 
president of the Lao People's Democratic Republic, on January 8, 
received Mr. Victor L. Tomseth who presented his credentials as 
ambassador extraordinary and plenipotentiary of the United 
States of America to Laos. 
  The Lao president welcomed the U.S. ambassador and expressed 
hope that he would further make contribution to the gradual 
improvement of the relationship between Laos and the U.S.A. in 
connection with the humanitarian cooperation in excavating for 
the remains of the Americans missing in action during the war. 
The Lao president confirmed the Lao Government's constant policy 
to render cooperation according to its real capability and 
conditions. 
  Concerning the narcotics issue, the Lao Government has 
exerted efforts and cooperated with international organisations 
in persuading mountainous people to eventually put an end to the 
poppy plantation and substitute it with crops and practise fixed 
highland farming. 
  The U.S. ambassador expressed thanks to the Lao authorities 
and people for their humanitarian cooperation and pledged to do 
his best to fulfill his diplomatic duty. 
  Mr. Victor L. Tomseth assumes the post to succeed Ambassador 
Charles B. Salmon Jr. 

</TEXT>

</DOC>

