<F P=100> ANNEX </F>
<F P=101> Japan </F>
<H3> <TI>   Reportage on Economic Framework Talks With U.S. </TI></H3>
<H4>   Under Secretary Spero Interviewed </H4>
<F P=102> OW1201054094 Tokyo Nikkei Telecom Database in Japanese 12 
Jan 94--FOR OFFICIAL USE ONLY </F>

<F P=103> OW1201054094 </F>
<F P=104>  Tokyo Nikkei Telecom Database </F>


<TEXT>
Language: <F P=105> Japanese </F>
Article Type:BFN 

<F P=106> [From NIHON KEIZAI SHIMBUN in Japanese 12 January Morning </F>
Edition] 
  [Text] On 11 January, a NIHON KEIZAI SHIMBUN reporter 
interviewed U.S. Under Secretary of State Joan Spero who is now 
on a visit to Japan to attend the Japan-U.S. economic framework 
talks. Referring to cuts in income tax, the senior U.S. official 
said: "I have heard the size of the cuts will be 6-7 trillion 
yen and I expect the cuts to lead to an expansion of Japan's 
domestic demand." She also said: "The effect of income tax cuts 
hinges on whether income tax and consumption tax are cut and 
raised simultaneously." The U.S. official suggested in a 
roundabout way that, the United States hopes Japan will defer 
raising consumption tax. 
  During the interview, Under Secretary of State Spero said: 
"Both Japan and the United Sates have committed to work on the 
macroeconomic area in their economic framework talks, and the 
U.S. Government has already made a noteworthy advance in cutting 
the budget deficit." Asked to comment on the stimulus measures 
under consideration by the Japanese Government, she declined, 
only saying: "All stimulus measures are matters to be decided by 
the Hosokawa government." But she added: "I expect the stimulus 
measures to lead to a further expansion of Japan's domestic 
demand and a cut in Japan's trade surplus. That is one of the 
goals of the Japan-U.S. economic framework talks." 
  Referring to the income tax reduction, which is a pillar of 
the stimulus measures, Spero said: "It has been reported that 
the scale of the reduction will be 6-7 trillion yen and I have 
heard the reports." But she pointed out the effect of the tax 
cuts hinges on the size of the raise in consumption tax and its 
timing, which is now fueling a debate in Japan. 
  In the interview, she also stressed the need for the 
Japanese 
Government to work for not only stimulus measures, but full 
deregulations and industrial restructuring. She said: "I hope 
the Hosokawa government will come to grips with the Japan-U.S. 
economic framework talks and work on a comprehensive economic 
plan after carrying out political reform." 

</TEXT>

</DOC>

