<F P=101> Japan </F>
<H3> <TI>   Reportage on Economic Framework Talks With U.S. </TI></H3>
<H4>   MITI Critical of U.S. Report </H4>
<F P=102> OW1201043194 Tokyo Nikkei Telecom Database in Japanese 12 
Jan 94--FOR OFFICIAL USE ONLY </F>

<F P=103> OW1201043194 </F>
<F P=104>  Tokyo Nikkei Telecom Database </F>


<TEXT>
Language: <F P=105> Japanese </F>
Article Type:BFN 

<F P=106> [From Tokyo NIHON KEIZAI SHIMBUN in Japanese 12 January </F>
Morning Edition] 
  [Text] The U.S. Government has compiled a report entitled: 
"In Search of a New Partnership" to seek understanding for the 
its position in the Japan-U.S. economic framework talks. The 
report clarifies the U.S. demands in the priority areas, 
including insurance, automobiles and auto parts, and 
telecommunications, claiming: "The United States is not seeking 
the setting of numerical targets. This report was compiled to 
dispel any misunderstanding" (according to the U.S. Embassy in 
Japan). However, Japan remains suspicious, saying, "A careful 
reading of the report shows the U.S. stance of being preoccupied 
with numerical targets remains unchanged" (according to the 
Ministry of International Trade and Industry [MITI]). 
  The report emphasizes: "The U.S. Government understands that 
trade should be determined by the market mechanism, and the 
framework talks are aimed at enhancing the opposite of managed 
trade [hi-kanri boeki] in Japan." 
  However, the report does cite some figures in several 
passages, such as: "While the market share of foreign insurance 
companies in advanced nations is 10 to 34 percent, their share 
in the Japanese market is merely 2 percent." Regarding 
automobiles and auto parts, the report says: "We demand that" 
the target of increasing Japanese carmakers' purchase of 
U.S.-made parts to $19 billion in fiscal 1994 "remains in place 
even in and after 1995." 
  MITI has reacted coldly to the report, claiming: "It merely 
avoids direct expressions; the U.S. stance of being preoccupied 
with numerical targets is still discernible." 

</TEXT>

</DOC>

