<F P=101> Japan </F>
<H3> <TI>   Vice Minister on Officials' Visits to Taiwan </TI></H3>
<F P=102>  OW1201025094 Tokyo ASAHI SHIMBUN in Japanese 11 Jan 94 
Morning Edition p 2--FOR OFFICIAL USE ONLY </F>

<F P=103> OW1201025094 </F>
<F P=104>  Tokyo ASAHI SHIMBUN </F>


<TEXT>
Language: <F P=105> Japanese </F>
Article Type:BFN 

  [Text] Kunihiko Saito, administrative vice minister for 
foreign affairs, commented on the issue of visits to Taiwan by 
Japanese cabinet members and other government officials at a 
press conference on 10 January. Saito said: "There has been no 
change in our basic policy of abiding by the principles and 
spirit of the Japan-China Joint Communique; that is, relations 
with Taiwan will be limited to areas other than political. In 
line with this policy, we will decide on each individual visit 
after looking carefully at the substance of the visit and other 
relevant factors." This is believed to leave the possibility 
open for visits by high-ranking government officials in 
connection with economic issues or international conferences. 
  Touching on a statement made by Tsutomu Hata, deputy prime 
minister and foreign minister, at a news conference in Beijing 
negating the possibility of cabinet members visiting Taiwan, 
Saito said: "This was in reply to the question `will there be 
visits to Taiwan in the near future, for instance, before the 
end of 1994?' It did not mean anything more than that." He 
indicated that the foreign minister's remark would not restrain 
visits by cabinet ministers to Taiwan in the future. 

</TEXT>

