<F P=101> Japan </F>
<H3> <TI>   Report on Changing UN PKO in Somalia Noted </TI></H3>
<F P=102>  OW1101124794 Tokyo ASAHI SHIMBUN in Japanese 10 Jan 94 
Morning Edition p 3--FOR OFFICIAL USE ONLY </F>

<F P=103> OW1101124794 </F>
<F P=104>  Tokyo ASAHI SHIMBUN </F>


<TEXT>
Language: <F P=105> Japanese </F>
Article Type:BFN 

  [Text] Regarding UN Secretary General Butrus 
Butrus-Ghali's report to the Security Council recommending a 
stop to efforts to disarm the fighting forces in Somalia by the 
use of force by UN troops, and switching to a more conventional 
type of PKO [peacekeeping operations], a senior Foreign Ministry 
official reacted calmly, claiming "this has been expected 
because the United States and other countries have expressed 
their wish to withdraw." 
  The government has, so far, shown understanding of the idea 
of "peace enforcement force," although "due to constitutional 
constraints, it would not be possible for Japan to participate." 
As a nonpermanent member of the Security Council, Japan has 
approved of the dispatch of forces to Somalia and the former 
Yugoslavia. 
  Therefore, it is interesting to see how the report will 
affect PKO in the former Yugoslavia, which has also been 
authorized to take action as a peace enforcement force similar 
to Somalia. 
  Some members of the Liberal Democratic Party and Shinseito 
[Japan Renewal Party] believe that if it is under UN command, 
Japan can also participate in peace enforcement forces. 
  However, right now, the government is even constrained in 
its 
participation in conventional PKO because the PKO Cooperation 
Law freezes participation in UN peacekeeping forces (PKF). The 
senior Foreign Ministry official said, "This report is not 
expected to affect Japan's policy on PKO." 
  A more active debate on the use of force in PKO is expected 
to occur in light of the Butrus-Ghali report. In anticipation 
of a review of the PKO Cooperation Law in the future, this 
report will certainly create a stir in the domestic debate on UN 
intervention in regional conflicts. 

</TEXT>

