<F P=100> ANNEX </F>
<F P=101> Japan </F>
<H3> <TI>   Accord Reached With Beef-Exporting Nations </TI></H3>
<F P=102>  OW1101100694 Tokyo SANKEI SHIMBUN in Japanese 9 Jan 94 
Morning Edition p 1 -- FOR OFFICIAL USE ONLY </F>

<F P=103> OW1101100694 </F>
<F P=104>  Tokyo SANKEI SHIMBUN </F>


<TEXT>
Language: <F P=105> Japanese </F>
Article Type:BFN 

  [Text] Following a decision at the new multilateral trade 
negotiations (Uruguay Round) to lower the tariff rate on beef, a 
Ministry of Agriculture, Forestry, and Fisheries [MAFF] source 
disclosed on 8 January that Japan had reached an agreement with 
beef-exporting nations, including the United States and 
Australia, regarding a new safeguard (emergency import 
restriction) which Japan can apply when beef imports increase 
rapidly. Reportedly, Australia, which is a beef-exporting 
nation, basically approves. Since requirements for its 
application will be eased, and definite action can be taken, the 
MAFF hopes it will be able to minimize the adverse affect to 
cattle farmers of lowering the tariff rate. 
  Currently, a 50-percent tariff is charged on beef but it 
will 
be reduced to 38.5 percent during the six years starting in 
1995, thanks to the agreement at the new round. 
  Under the new safeguard, Japan will be able to increase the 
tariff rate to 50 percent, which is the current rate, if an 
import amount, calculated on the basis of beef imports for every 
quarter period, increases by 17 percent or more compared to that 
of the same quarter of the previous year. Under the current 
safeguard, which was introduced under a Japan-U.S. accord in 
1988, the tariff rate can be increased by 25 percent if the 
annual import quantity grows by 20 percent or more. Domestic 
cattle farmers are critical of the current safeguard, saying 
that "requirements for its application are severe and it is not 
a definite measure." 
  Moreover, the new safeguard can be applied to chilled and 
frozen beef separately. 
  However, the reality is that the quantity of imported beef 
is 
rapidly increasing even though the tariff rate is 50 percent. 
Moreover, it seems that cattle farmers may have doubts about the 
effect of the new safeguard should primary factors of beef 
import expansion, including further appreciation of the yen, be 
felt. 

</TEXT>

</DOC>

