<F P=101> Japan </F>
<H3> <TI>   SDPJ, Sakigake Members Study Party Realignment </TI></H3>
<F P=102>  OW1201060494 Tokyo ASAHI SHIMBUN in Japanese 11 Jan 94 
Morning Edition p 5--FOR OFFICIAL USE ONLY </F>

<F P=103> OW1201060494 </F>
<F P=104>  Tokyo ASAHI SHIMBUN </F>


<TEXT>
Language: <F P=105> Japanese </F>
Article Type:BFN 

  [Text] Right-wing members of the ruling Social Democratic 
Party of Japan [SDPJ] and members of Sakigake [Harbinger] 
inaugurated a study group on the evening of 10 January, to press 
for a realignment of political parties; the group held a meeting 
at a Tokyo hotel that evening. A total of 13 members -- 9 
members including former Dietmen from the SDPJ and 4 members 
from Sakigake -- attended the meeting. 
  Yoshito Sengok, who is a former member of the House of 
Representatives and affiliated with the SDPJ, and Kenichiro 
Sato, chief of the Election Bureau of Sakigake, will play the 
role of contact points. The study group will be called about 
twice a month in order for members to exchange views on ways to 
pass political reform bills in the Diet and prepare campaign 
strategies for the combined electoral system of single-seat 
constituency and proportional representation under debate in the 
Diet. 

</TEXT>

</DOC>

