<F P=100> ANNEX </F>
<F P=101> Japan </F>
<H3> <TI>   Reportage on Economic Framework Talks With U.S. </TI></H3>
<H4>   Officials `Alarmed' at U.S. Moves </H4>
<F P=102> OW1201040194 Tokyo NIHON KEIZAI SHIMBUN in Japanese 11 Jan 
94 Morning Edition p 5--FOR OFFICIAL USE ONLY </F>

<F P=103> OW1201040194 </F>
<F P=104>  Tokyo NIHON KEIZAI SHIMBUN </F>


<TEXT>
Language: <F P=105> Japanese </F>
Article Type:BFN 

  [Text] The Japan-U.S. economic consultations are to face a 
major hurdle this week, with the vice ministerial-level meeting 
on automobiles and auto parts -- the issue of most concern in 
the economic framework talks -- to be held in Tokyo for four 
days from 11 January. 
  Jeffrey Garten, U.S. under secretary of commerce, who 
represents the U.S. Government, wants to meet with top 
executives of major auto manufacturers like Toyota Motor 
Corporation while in Japan, in order to talk directly with the 
industry on the question of buying U.S.-made parts--the question 
on which government-level talks are making no headway. The 
Japanese Government, on the other hand, wants to reaffirm its 
position of not adopting any plans on procuring U.S.-made parts 
for 1995 and thereafter. 
  Meanwhile, in the area of construction, while the deadline 
for the U.S. Government deciding whether to retaliate against 
Japan or not is drawing near to 20 January, informal 
working-level talks have started in Tokyo, and the Japanese 
Government will make final efforts to prevent eventual 
retaliation. 
  Under Secretary Garten will meet with Japanese Government 
officials like Sozaburo Okamatsu, deputy vice minister for 
international trade and industry, in the formal talks, but has 
also asked to meet with people like Tatsuro Toyoda, president of 
Toyota Motor, and Nobuhiko Kawamoto, president of Honda Motor 
Company. He claims the primary purpose of the meeting is to 
hear auto industry views, but it is possible he will personally 
ask the industry to expand the purchase of U.S.-made products. 
Specifically, the United States is hopeful that Japan's plan of 
buying "about $19 billion in 1994" will be continued into 1995 
and thereafter. 
  On the contrary, the Japanese Government is poised to reject 
continued setting of such a purchase plan in the vice 
ministerial-level meeting. Even on the question of setting 
objective criteria as a way of measuring the extent of market 
liberalization, the government will persist in the position: 
"Criteria that can lead to agreeing on targets cannot be 
accepted" (to quote an official of the Ministry of International 
Trade and Industry). 
  In fact, Under Secretary of State Spero, who is one of the 
U.S. officials in charge of the framework talks, arrived before 
Under Secretary of Commerce Garten; and during her 10-12 January 
stay, is due to meet with people from political and business 
circles like Gaishi Hiraiwa, chairman of the Federation of 
Economic Organizations of Japan [Keidanren], as well as Deputy 
Chief Cabinet Secretary Hatoyama. In the meetings, she is 
expected to urge facilitation of the framework talks, while 
calling for prompt action to stimulate the economy. 
  Some people interpret this position of U.S. officials 
wanting 
to deal directly with Japanese industry, as a "revelation of 
mistrust in Japanese bureaucrats," and government offices like 
the Ministry of International Trade and Industry, the Ministry 
of Foreign Affairs, and the Ministry of Finance are becoming 
alarmed. 
  One goal in the economic framework talks is to enable the 
Japan-U.S. summit--to be held in Washington on 11 February--to 
announce an agreement on the three top priority areas of 
automobiles and auto parts, insurance, and government 
procurements. Both the Japanese and U.S. Governments agree that 
"by all means, we must come to a successful conclusion" (to 
quote an official of the Foreign Ministry), but, so far, not 
much progress has been made even though only one month is left 
before the summit. 

</TEXT>

</DOC>

<DOC>
<DOCNO> FBIS3-47402 </DOCNO>
<HT>    "dreas008__a94017" </HT>


<HEADER>
<AU>   FBIS-EAS-94-008-A </AU>
Document Type:Daily Report 
<DATE1>  12 January 1994 </DATE1>

