<F P=100> ANNEX </F>
<F P=101> Japan </F>
<H3> <TI>   Spero Asks Tokyo To Work on Trade Issues </TI></H3>
<F P=102>  OW1201150394 Tokyo ASAHI SHIMBUN in Japanese 12 Jan 94 
Morning Edition p 11--FOR OFFICIAL USE ONLY </F>

<F P=103> OW1201150394 </F>
<F P=104>  Tokyo ASAHI SHIMBUN </F>


<TEXT>
Language: <F P=105> Japanese </F>
Article Type:BFN 

  [Text] On 11 January, Joan E. Spero, U.S. under secretary 
of state for economic and agricultural affairs, speaking on the 
Japan-U.S. framework trade talks, said: "There are priority 
areas such as government procurement, automobiles, and auto 
parts. After enactment of the political reform bills, we would 
like the Japanese Government to shift its attention and work on 
these priorities." She made the request during a meeting with 
Yukio Hatoyama, deputy chief cabinet secretary, at the prime 
minister's official residence on the same day. 
  In response, Hatoyama, while maintaining that setting 
numerical targets is unacceptable, said: "I feel that it is 
possible for Japan and the United States to hold talks to work 
out something that is acceptable to both sides." 

</TEXT>

