<F P=101> Japan </F>
<H3> <TI>   Article Views U.S. Moves To Restore Super 301 </TI></H3>
<F P=102>  OW1301043894 Tokyo Nikkei Telecom Database in Japanese 13 
Jan 94--FOR OFFICIAL USE ONLY </F>

<F P=103> OW1301043894 </F>
<F P=104>  Tokyo Nikkei Telecom Database </F>


<TEXT>
Language: <F P=105> Japanese </F>
Article Type:BFN 

<F P=106> [Article by correspondent Shigeru Komago; from NIHON KEIZAI </F>
SHIMBUN in Japanese 13 January Morning Edition] 
  [Text] U.S. Trade Representative Mickey Kantor has said 
that the possibility of restoring the Super 301 provision of the 
1988 Omnibus Trade Act through a presidential decree is under 
consideration. He is believed to have made the remark to shake 
up the Japanese Government, which continues to take a hard-line 
attitude toward the Japan-U.S. economic framework talks. 
  It is highly possible that the United States will restore 
the 
Super 301 provision through presidential decree if the 
Japan-U.S. economic framework talks end in failure, but the 
United States is not necessarily confident it will have the 
desired effect. 
  A bill on restoration of the Super 301 provision is expected 
to be introduced to Congress in late January, when its recess 
ends, and it is widely believed the bill will be supported by 
Congress. 
  The U.S. Government has explored ways to restore the 
provision through presidential decree since last year, before 
Congress moved to enact the bill. It began to look at how to 
restore the provision in December when Japan and the United 
States were locked in confrontation over the Japan-U.S. economic 
framework talks and the multilateral trade negotiations [the 
Uruguay Round of GATT] reached their conclusion without some 
U.S. complaints having been addressed. 
  But the Japanese do not expect restoration of the provision 
to have the desired effect. A source traveling with the 
Japanese delegation said, "there is no need for Japan to be 
furious at all." If the United States restores this one-sided 
sanction so soon after conclusion of the Uruguay Round, it would 
lead European and Asian nations to criticize the United States. 
The U.S. Government must, therefore, be cautious about invoking 
the provision. 
  It could create a situation in which Japan and the United 
States come to a showdown on the eve of the scheduled Japan-U.S. 
summit talks in February. How will Prime Minister Hosokawa and 
ministers of the coalition government respond to the issue? If 
government leaders rush to instruct Japanese negotiators to make 
absurd concessions at the Japan-U.S. economic framework talks, 
the United States will get what it wants. It goes without 
saying that whatever the U.S. attitude, the Japanese Government 
needs to decide on concrete measures on its own to fulfill the 
prime minister's public pledge to expand Japanese domestic 
demand and cut its current account surplus by opening the 
Japanese market. 

</TEXT>

</DOC>

