<H3> <TI>   Hosokawa Said Likely To Visit PRC 20-21 Mar </TI></H3>
<F P=102>  OW1001144094 Tokyo MAINICHI SHIMBUN in Japanese 10 Jan 94 
Morning Edition p 1--FOR OFFICIAL USE ONLY </F>

<F P=103> OW1001144094 </F>
<F P=104>  Tokyo MAINICHI SHIMBUN </F>


<TEXT>
Language: <F P=105> Japanese </F>
Article Type:BFN 

<F P=106> [By reporter Eriko Kawaji] </F>
  [Text] Beijing, 9 Jan -- Plans will be worked out for 
scheduling Prime Minister Morihiro Hosokawa's visit to China on 
20- 21 March, according to a source accompanying Tsutomu Hata, 
deputy prime minister and concurrently foreign minister, in the 
latter's Chinese visit. The source made this disclosure on 9 
January. Concerning Prime Minister Hosokawa's visit to China, 
Hata and Qian Qichen, his Chinese counterpart, had earlier 
agreed at their 8 January meeting in Beijing on working out 
plans for Hosokawa's visit at an early date. 
  In the backdrop of the prime minister's making firm his 
intention to visit China as early as March is the fact that 
although he has visited the United States and the ROK since his 
inauguration, he still has not visited China, which, along with 
the United States, is a focal point of Japanese diplomacy. 
Furthermore, Prime Minister Hosokawa plans to work out details 
regarding the total value of the planned yen loan to China -- 
the fourth such loan program -- which Foreign Minister Hata put 
on the rails during his visit there. 
  Regarding the schedule of Hosokawa's visit, Chinese 
officials 
have requested a 3-day visit starting 19 January. Japanese 
officials, however, are working primarily around a plan for a 
visit on 20-21 March, taking advantage of consecutive holidays. 
This plan also takes into consideration the schedule of Diet 
sessions, among other matters. 

</TEXT>

