<F P=100> NORTHEAST ASIA </F>
<F P=101> Japan </F>
<H3> <TI>   Officials Report on Progress in Framework Talks </TI></H3>
<F P=102>  OW1301003894 Tokyo KYODO in English 0014 GMT 13 Jan 94 </F>
<F P=103> OW1301003894 </F>
<F P=104>  Tokyo KYODO </F>


<TEXT>
Language: <F P=105> English </F>
Article Type:BFN 

  [Text] Washington, Jan. 12 KYODO -- The United States and 
Japan may hold a ministerial meeting to address the bilateral 
framework trade talks if no breakthrough is reached at 
subcabinet-level negotiations, U.S. Trade Representative Mickey 
Kantor said Wednesday [13 January]. 
  The two governments have scheduled at least two rounds of 
framework negotiations at deputy ministerial level prior to the 
summit meeting between Prime Minister Morihiro Hosokawa and 
President Bill Clinton on February 11. 
  So far, neither Tokyo nor Washington has raised the 
possibility of a ministerial meeting. 
  But Kantor told a news conference Wednesday that "there will 
be probably discussions at the ministerial level" following the 
deputies' meetings. 
  Meanwhile, Japanese officials reported progress on framework 
talks on financial services held in Washington Wednesday. 
  A Japanese official who took part in the negotiations said 
he 
expects an interim report on financial services to be completed 
by the time the first deputies' meeting takes place in 
Washington on January 24. 
  The official warned, however, that conclusion of an interim 
report does not mean that the two sides have settled their 
differences on substantive issues, since the document contains 
primarily a wish list of market access issues that both sides 
want to be addressed. 
  According to the framework accord concluded last July, the 
two countries have until July this year to complete negotiations 
on financial services. 

</TEXT>

</DOC>

