<F P=100> NORTHEAST ASIA </F>
<F P=101> Japan </F>
<H3> <TI>   Reaction to Kantor's Remarks on Reviving 301 </TI></H3>
<H4>   Takemura To Urge `Prudence' </H4>
<F P=102> OW1301050194 Tokyo NHK General Television Network in 
Japanese 0300 GMT 13 Jan 94 </F>

<F P=103> OW1301050194 </F>
<F P=104>  Tokyo NHK General Television Network </F>


<TEXT>
Language: <F P=105> Japanese </F>
Article Type:BFN 

<F P=106> [Announcer-read report over video; from the "NHK News" </F>
program] 
  [Text] Chief Cabinet Secretary Masayoshi Takemura 
commented this morning at a news conference on U.S. Trade 
Representative Michael Kantor's remark that the U.S. Government 
is studying the possibility of reviving the Super 301 provision 
of the 1988 Omnibus Trade Act. 
  The provision stipulates retaliation against trading nations 
that refuse to liberalize their markets or discriminate against 
U.S. exports. 
  Insisting that such action would go against the spirit of 
Japan- U.S. economic consultations, Takemura said he would urge 
prudence on part of the United States. 
  [Begin Takemura recording] Our agreement is that we should 
maximize our efforts at dialogue. I think what they are 
proposing would go against the spirit of dialogue. I would like 
to ask that they be prudent as far as remarks on exercising the 
Super 301 provision are concerned. [end recording] 
  Takemura's comments indicated the government would ask the 
United States to be cautious about reviving the Super 301 
provisions. 

</TEXT>

</DOC>

<DOC>
<DOCNO> FBIS3-47468 </DOCNO>
<HT>    "dreas009_a_94004" </HT>


<HEADER>
<AU>   FBIS-EAS-94-009 </AU>
Document Type:Daily Report 
<DATE1>  13 January 1994 </DATE1>

</HEADER>

<F P=100> NORTHEAST ASIA </F>
<F P=101> Japan </F>
<H3> <TI>   Reaction to Kantor's Remarks on Reviving 301 </TI></H3>
<H4>   Further on Takemura Response </H4>
<F P=102> OW1301051294 Tokyo KYODO in English 0304 GMT 13 Jan 94 </F>
<F P=103> OW1301051294 </F>
<F P=104>  Tokyo KYODO </F>


<TEXT>
Language: <F P=105> English </F>
Article Type:BFN 

  [Text] Tokyo, Jan. 13 KYODO -- Japan voiced concern on 
Thursday [13 January] over a possible move by the United States 
to revive the "Super 301" trade measure through an executive 
order. 
  Saying Tokyo and Washington have agreed to do their utmost 
to 
achieve progress in bilateral framework trade talks, Chief 
Cabinet Secretary Masayoshi Takemura told a news conference that 
the resurrection of the U.S. measure would run counter to the 
accord. 
  "We want the U.S. to act cautiously," the top government 
spokesman said. 
  "Super 301," in effect from 1988 to 1990, required the U.S. 
Government to conduct an annual review of trade barriers abroad 
and impose trade sanctions if those barriers were not removed 
within a year. 
  Takemura's comment came after U.S. Trade Representative 
Mickey Kantor said Wednesday the administration of President 
Bill Clinton may renew the punitive measure through an executive 
order in connection with bilateral trade "framework" 
negotiations. 
  "That would be an option," Kantor told a group of Japanese 
reporters. 
  Touching on the framework talks, Kantor said Washington will 
insist on setting quantitative criteria to gauge the openness of 
Japanese markets. 
  Japanese and U.S. negotiators have become bogged down on how 
to define and set "objective criteria" in the negotiations, 
which are being held under the bilateral trade framework accord 
reached last July. 
  Washington wants to use the level of imports in other group 
of seven major industrialized nations as the "norm" for Japan to 
follow. 
  Japanese officials call the U.S. position unacceptable, 
saying such measures would amount to setting aside a specific 
market share for foreign goods and services, tantamount to 
managed trade. 
  Earlier Thursday, a government source also expressed 
displeasure about the potential revival of "Super 301." 
  "Negotiations will be impossible if they are based on 
retaliatory actions," the source said. 
  Stressing that Tokyo will continue efforts to further open 
the nation's markets, the source said Japan and the U.S. should 
talk with each other on the principle of an equal partnership. 
  Prime Minister Morihiro Hosokawa will meet Clinton on 
February 11 in Washington to assess progress in the framework 
talks. 

</TEXT>

</DOC>

<DOC>
<DOCNO> FBIS3-47469 </DOCNO>
<HT>    "dreas009_a_94005" </HT>


<HEADER>
<AU>   FBIS-EAS-94-009 </AU>
