<F P=100> NORTHEAST ASIA </F>
<F P=101> Japan </F>
<H3> <TI>   Tokyo, Washington To Hold Talks on Microchips </TI></H3>
<F P=102>  OW1301073494 Tokyo KYODO in English 0713 GMT 13 Jan 94 </F>
<F P=103> OW1301073494 </F>
<F P=104>  Tokyo KYODO </F>


<TEXT>
Language: <F P=105> English </F>
Article Type:BFN 

  [Text] Tokyo, Jan. 13 KYODO -- Japan and the United States 
will hold emergency talks next Wednesday in Tokyo about the 
foreign share of the Japanese semiconductor market, the vice 
trade minister said Thursday [13 January]. 
  Vice International Trade and Industry Minister Hideaki 
Kumano 
told a press conference that the Japanese side will seek the 
understanding of their U.S. counterparts by explaining the 
circumstances surrounding a recent fall in the share of foreign 
microchips in Japan. 
  Although the ratio has dropped the absolute quantity of 
foreign microchips sold in Japan has increased, Kumano said. 
  The foreign share of Japan's microchips market during the 
July-September period of 1993 fell below 20 percent for the 
third consecutive quarterly drop. 
  Dissatisfied with the results, U.S. Trade Representative 
Mickey Kantor asked Japan for an emergency meeting on the matter 
in January. 
  The 20 percent is cited in a 1991 bilateral semiconductor 
trade pact as the share level of foreign-made microchips in 
Japan expected to be achieved by the end of 1992. 
  Under the pact, emergency meetings are provided for if the 
objectives of the arrangement are not being achieved. No such 
consultations have been held so far. 
  The share of foreign microchips in Japan, as calculated by 
the U.S. formula, reached 20.2 percent in the last quarter of 
1992, heading off U.S. sanctions, but has fallen since, to 19.6 
percent in the first quarter, 19.2 percent in the second 
quarter, and 18.1 percent in the third quarter of 1993. 

</TEXT>

</DOC>

