<F P=100> NORTHEAST ASIA </F>
<F P=101> Japan </F>
<H3> <TI>   Nissan To Shift Sunny Production to U.S. </TI></H3>
<F P=102>  OW1201142194 Tokyo KYODO in English 1107 GMT 12 Jan 94 </F>
<F P=103> OW1201142194 </F>
<F P=104>  Tokyo KYODO </F>


<TEXT>
Language: <F P=105> English </F>
Article Type:BFN 

  [Text] Tokyo, Jan. 12 KYODO -- Nissan Motor Co. will 
shift to the United States all its manufacturing operations for 
the Sunny model which is sold there, the company's head said 
Wednesday [12 January]. 
  Upon unveiling the new Sunny model, Nissan President 
Yoshifumi Tsuji said the switch was prompted by the appreciation 
of the yen. 
  Nissan has already started to locally manufacture about 70 
percent of Sunny cars sold in the U.S. market. 
  Just less than 120,000 vehicles of 165,000 Sunny cars sold 
in 
the U.S. last year were locally made, with the remainder 
imported from Japan. 
  Tsuji said its new manufacturing plant in Tennessee will be 
in charge of production of all Sunnys from late this year. The 
cars produced there will be put on the U.S. market starting 
1995. 
  Nissan's Zama plant in Kanagawa Prefecture will continue 
making Sunnys for the domestic market, but its production will 
be phased out, as the operation is gradually moved to the Kanda 
plant in Kyushu as part of the company's restructuring program. 

</TEXT>

