<H3> <TI>   Tokyo, Moscow Postpone Talks on Islands </TI></H3>
<F P=102>  OW1301093294 Tokyo KYODO in English 0917 GMT 13 Jan 94 </F>
<F P=103> OW1301093294 </F>
<F P=104>  Tokyo KYODO </F>


<TEXT>
Language: <F P=105> English </F>
Article Type:BFN 

  [Text] Tokyo, Jan. 13 KYODO -- Japan and Russia will 
indefinitely postpone planned working-level talks on a bilateral 
territorial dispute originally set for late January, a top 
Foreign Ministry official said Thursday [13 January]. 
  The meeting, scheduled in Moscow as the first talks on the 
territorial row between the two sides since Russian President 
Boris Yeltsin visited Japan last October, is being postponed at 
Russia's request, the official said on condition of anonymity. 
  The official quoted Russian officials as citing as an 
obstacle mobility of personnel in the wake of Russia's 
parliamentary elections in December. 
  Japan claims four Russian-held islands off the northernmost 
main island of Hokkaido. The islands -- Shikotan, Kunashiri, 
Etorofu and the Habomai islets -- were seized by the former 
Soviet Union at the end of World War II. 

</TEXT>

