<F P=101> Japan </F>
<H3> <TI>   Paris Club Likely To Defer Russian Debt </TI></H3>
<F P=102>  OW1301120694 Tokyo KYODO in English 0748 GMT 13 Jan 94 </F>
<F P=103> OW1301120694 </F>
<F P=104>  Tokyo KYODO </F>


<TEXT>
Language: <F P=105> English </F>
Article Type:BFN 

  [Text] Tokyo, Jan. 13 KYODO -- The Paris Club of official 
creditors appears likely to agree on deferring 1 billion dollars 
or so in Russian debt payments falling due in March or April, 
government sources said Thursday [13 January]. 
  The agreement is expected as early as January 17 when the 
Paris Club holds a meeting, the sources said. The Paris Club is 
an informal grouping of creditor nations which meet regularly in 
the French capital. 
  Russia's official creditors so far have agreed to reschedule 
some 15 billion dollars of the country's foreign debt falling 
due last year for 10 years, with a five-year grace period for 
interest payments. 
  They are also to defer Russian debt payments falling due in 
1994 on condition that Russia and the International Monetary 
Fund agree on economic reforms needed for IMF loans. 
  But a majority of Paris Club members now believe that a debt 
rescheduling deal for Russian debt payments falling due by April 
is needed unconditionally as a temporary measure because Russia 
faces slow progress in economic reforms due to political unrest, 
the sources said. 

</TEXT>

</DOC>

