<F P=100> NORTHEAST ASIA </F>
<F P=101> Japan </F>
<H3> <TI>   Government Fixes Price of Imported Rice </TI></H3>
<F P=102>  OW1301132194 Tokyo KYODO in English 1223 GMT 13 Jan 94 </F>
<F P=103> OW1301132194 </F>
<F P=104>  Tokyo KYODO </F>


<TEXT>
Language: <F P=105> English </F>
Article Type:BFN 

  [Text] Tokyo, Jan. 13 KYODO -- The Rice Price Council on 
Thursday [13 January] approved a Farm Ministry plan to set the 
government selling prices of imported table-use rice at 60 to 84 
percent of the average selling price of standard Japanese rice, 
ministry officials said. 
  The approval came when the Agriculture, Forestry and 
Fisheries Ministry briefed the government advisory council on 
the plan at an informal council meeting, the officials said. 
  They said the ministry is likely to make an official 
decision 
next week on the prices of imported rice, which is scheduled to 
go on sale nationwide in Japan next month. The imported rice 
will be blended with Japanese rice for sale to consumers. 
  Japan is importing rice on an emergency basis due to a bad 
crop in 1993. 
  The prices will be based on two categories of rice -- 
long-grain and short- or medium-grain -- and on the country of 
origin, the officials said. 
  Among the imports, rice from the United States and top-grade 
rice from China, both short- or medium-grain, will be sold for 
16,898 yen per 60 kilograms, 84 percent of the average selling 
price of standard Japanese rice. 
  Long-grain non-glutinous rice from Thailand will be sold for 
11,992 yen per 60 kilograms, 60 percent of the Japanese rice 
price. 
  Major supermarket chains, meanwhile, have started studying 
plans for selling imported rice to consumers. 
  Daiei Inc. said it plans to sell blends of imported and 
domestic rice and expects to eventually replace 100 percent 
top-grade domestic rice with blended rice. 
  Daiei officials said 100 percent imported rice is likely to 
be sold at prices 30 to 50 percent lower than domestic rice. 
  Ito-Yokado Co. said it plans to test-market imported rice at 
limited outlets, beginning in February. 
  Restaurant chain Skylark Co. declined comment on the 
possibility of cutting menu prices by using imported rice. 
  Frozen food manufacturer Nichirei Inc. also declined comment 
on possible price cuts for its products through the use of 
imported rice. The company last year raised its prices for 
frozen rice-based foods. 

</TEXT>

