<F P=102>  OW1301131994 Tokyo KYODO in English 1242 GMT 13 Jan 94 </F>
<F P=103> OW1301131994 </F>
<F P=104>  Tokyo KYODO </F>


<TEXT>
Language: <F P=105> English </F>
Article Type:BFN 

  [Text] Tokyo, Jan. 13 KYODO -- The government and the 
ruling coalition plan to compile a budget plan for the next 
fiscal year by February 10, government sources said Thursday [13 
January]. 
  According to their budget-drafting schedule, the ruling 
coalition will work out guidelines on February 3 for compilation 
of the budget and tax reforms for fiscal 1994, starting in April. 
  Based on this, on February 5 the Finance Ministry will 
announce its budgetary plan, which is likely to be adopted as a 
government proposal with few changes on February 10, just in 
time for the summit meeting in Washington between Prime Minister 
Morihiro Hosokawa and U.S. President Bill Clinton. 
  Government sources said the biggest point for debate will be 
how to finance a planned reduction in the income tax. 
  The Social Democratic Party [of Japan], an important force 
in 
the coalition, has been opposed to raising the current 3 percent 
consumption tax rate to offset the income tax cut, an idea 
pushed by the Finance Ministry. 

