<H3> <TI>   Diet Panel Drafts Bill To Cut Administration </TI></H3>
<F P=102>  OW1201143594 Tokyo KYODO in English 1230 GMT 12 Jan 94 </F>
<F P=103> OW1201143594 </F>
<F P=104>  Tokyo KYODO </F>


<TEXT>
Language: <F P=105> English </F>
Article Type:BFN 

  [Text] Tokyo, Jan. 12 KYODO -- A panel of Diet members 
from several political parties drafted a bill Wednesday [12 
January] to establish within parliament an organization that 
will work to streamline the administration, panel members said. 
  The group led by Naoto Kan, a House of Representatives 
member 
of the United Social Democratic Party (Shaminren), will submit 
the bill to the next ordinary session of the Diet beginning on 
January 31, they said. Prime Minister Morihiro Hosokawa serves 
as adviser to the group. 
  Under the panel's plan, the organization would hear 
complaints from the public about the administration, check such 
opinions and report the outcome of the study to the House of 
Representatives speaker or the House of Councillors president. 
  The commission would also advise the lower house speaker or 
the upper house president on enacting or abolishing laws for the 
purpose of cutting administrative organizations. 
  The planned organization would have the right to demand 
administrative bodies to submit documents and to open hearings. 
  The Management and Coordination Agency plans to set up a 
similar organization in the Prime Minister's Office, but the 
group led by Kan doubts the administration can make the 
appropriate cuts on its own, they said. 

</TEXT>

