<H3> <TI>   Hosokawa Denies Plan To Reshuffle Cabinet </TI></H3>
<F P=102>  OW1301100994 Tokyo KYODO in English 0947 GMT 13 Jan 94 </F>
<F P=103> OW1301100994 </F>
<F P=104>  Tokyo KYODO </F>


<TEXT>
Language: <F P=105> English </F>
Article Type:BFN 

  [Text] Tokyo, Jan. 13 KYODO -- Prime Minister Morihiro 
Hosokawa denied press reports Thursday [13 January] that he is 
considering reshuffling the cabinet immediately after the 
expected passage of political reform bills at the end of this 
month. 
  Hosokawa told reporters that he is "not at all considering" 
a 
cabinet reshuffle. 
  The premier also said the government plans to retain the 
post 
of a state minister in charge of political reform after the 
expected passage of the political reform bills. Sadao Yamahana, 
former chairman of the Social Democratic Party, currently holds 
the post. 
  The YOMIURI SHIMBUN reported Thursday that Hosokawa 
discussed 
the plan to reshuffle the cabinet with Shinseito (Japan Renewal 
Party) co-leader Ichiro Ozawa at the end of last year and is 
studying the timing and scale of the change. 
  The YOMIURI said the reshuffle would be on a limited scale, 
though it was intended to replace Chief Cabinet Secretary 
Masayoshi Takemura and a few other ministers. 
  Takemura, who advocated concessions to the opposition 
Liberal 
Democratic Party (LDP) on the bills, is likely to be retained in 
the cabinet with a new post, the YOMIURI said. 
  Ozawa, former LDP secretary general, takes an uncompromising 
stance to the LDP. 
  Shinseito is offering cabinet posts to [Social Democratic 
Party of Japan] SDP [SDPJ] executives calling for tightening 
control on party members, sources said. Several SDP[J] House of 
Councillors members have expressed opposition to the bills and 
could vote against them or abstain. 
  The government-proposed package that Hosokawa has vowed to 
push through the Diet during its current session is pending 
before the upper house. 

</TEXT>

