<F P=100> NORTHEAST ASIA </F>
<F P=101> Japan </F>
<H3> <TI>   LDP Group Criticizes Shinseito, Komeito </TI></H3>
<F P=102>  OW1201094394 Tokyo KYODO in English 0922 GMT 12 Jan 94 </F>
<F P=103> OW1201094394 </F>
<F P=104>  Tokyo KYODO </F>


<TEXT>
Language: <F P=105> English </F>
Article Type:BFN 

  [Text] Tokyo, Jan. 12 KYODO -- A group of Liberal 
Democratic Party (LDP) legislators on Wednesday [12 January] 
blasted two key forces within the coalition government of Prime 
Minister Morihiro Hosokawa for their alleged "fascist nature." 
  "We must see through and fight the fascist trend that has 
been clearly emerging in politics for the past half year since 
the inauguration of the Hosokawa cabinet," the group said in a 
statement. 
  All group members are legislators of the powerful House of 
Representatives. 
  The 22-member group of the main opposition asserted that 
Shinseito (Japan Renewal Party) and Komeito, major components in 
the seven-party coalition, want political reform to be achieved 
so as to gain absolute power. 
  A change in the system for House of Representatives 
elections, a centerpiece of the government-sponsored reform 
package, "is a weapon definitely necessary for a political bloc 
forged by Shinseito and Komeito." It described the two parties 
as having a "fascist nature" in their lust for power. 
  "We are saying what nobody else has said, though he or she 
has noticed the signs," lower house member Katsuhiko Shirakawa 
told a news conference. 
  Calling Shinseito and Komeito "authoritarian and autocratic" 
forces, another lower house member, Minoru Noda, said the two 
parties will continue to threaten the nation's parliamentary 
democracy. 
  The coalition and the LDP have been at loggerheads over the 
course of political reform aimed at ending rampant corruption in 
Japanese public life. 
  Hosokawa has staked his political fate on enactment of 
necessary legislation by the January 29 close of the current 
Diet session. 
  Shirakawa and other LDP lower house legislators told 
reporters that they will ask lower house and House of 
Councillors legislators of other political parties to join the 
parliamentary group, temporarily called "The Association of 
Solidarity for Freedom." 
  Shinseito's co-leader, Ichiro Ozawa, is one of the most 
powerful politicians in the coalition and was apparently 
instrumental in establishing the coalition government last 
August after dislodging the LDP from a 38-year-old grip on power 
following the general elections a month earlier. 
  Ozawa is believed to have still exerted strong influences 
behind the scenes and have a strong tie with Komeito Secretary 
General Yuichi Ichikawa. 
  Political analysts said Shinseito and Komeito may unite as 
the next stage of rallying political forces comes around. 

</TEXT>

</DOC>

