<H3> <TI>   LDP Group Accuses Coalition of `Fascist' Stance </TI></H3>
<F P=102>  OW1301081894 Tokyo KYODO in English 0744 GMT 13 Jan 94 </F>
<F P=103> OW1301081894 </F>
<F P=104>  Tokyo KYODO </F>


<TEXT>
Language: <F P=105> English </F>
Article Type:BFN 

  [Text] Tokyo, Jan. 13 KYODO -- A group of Liberal 
Democratic Party (LDP) lawmakers on Thursday [13 January] 
accused the ruling coalition of having a "fascist" political 
stance and called for the protection of democracy. 
  "The governing coalition's management of parliamentary 
affairs and its political stance are extremely autocratic and 
authoritarian, and it is undeniable that it is moving in the 
direction of fascist politics," the group said in a statement. 
  "This is a crisis of democracy, and it is now an urgent 
political task to launch an antifascism and prodemocracy 
movement," it said. 
  The group led by House of Representatives member Yoshinobu 
Shimamura issued the appeal after a meeting that brought 
together 32 LDP legislators, one former LDP lawmaker and 31 
proxies of politicians. 
  It also sought advance enactment of anticorruption measures 
without changing the electoral system for the lower house. 
  The lower house election system should be amended along with 
the systems for House of Councillors and local government polls 
after ruling and opposition parties reach a consensus, the group 
said. 
  Prime Minister Morihiro Hosokawa has staked his political 
fate on enactment of a reform package featuring electoral 
changes and stricter controls on campaign funding before the 
current extraordinary Diet session ends on January 29. 

</TEXT>

</DOC>

