<F P=100> NORTHEAST ASIA </F>
<F P=101> Japan </F>
<H3> <TI>   Ozawa Agrees To Resume News Conferences 17 Jan </TI></H3>
<F P=102>  OW1201100994 Tokyo KYODO in English 0943 GMT 12 Jan 94 </F>
<F P=103> OW1201100994 </F>
<F P=104>  Tokyo KYODO </F>


<TEXT>
Language: <F P=105> English </F>
Article Type:BFN 

  [Text] Tokyo, Jan. 12 KYODO -- Ruling party Shinseito 
(Japan Renewal Party) co-leader Ichiro Ozawa will resume his 
press conference Monday [17 January] for the first time in more 
than two months, his office said Wednesday. 
  The resumption apparently means that Ozawa has agreed to 
Shinseito officials' requests that he meet with reporters. 
  "We hope to respect and understand each other by resuming 
the 
press conferences," the office said. 
  Ozawa had refused to hold press briefings since early 
November as negotiations between him and the media organizations 
deadlocked over his ban of journalists of two major dailies -- 
the NIHON KEIZAI SHIMBUN and the SANKEI SHIMBUN -- from his 
press meetings. 
  Ozawa, a powerful figure of the coalition government led by 
Prime Minister Morihiro Hosokawa, in late October began 
excluding the two papers' reporters from his news conferences, 
saying their news coverage on him had been inaccurate. 
  Ozawa's office said the two papers will be allowed to attend 
the Monday meeting. 
  The Monday meeting will be held for the first time since 
November 8, when Ozawa held a press conference to tell reporters 
that he had accepted 5 million yen from scandal-plagued Kajima 
Corp. as a legal political donation. 
  The Tuesday edition of the South Korean daily TONG-A ILBO 
carried an interview with Ozawa, in which he was quoted as 
saying that the Japanese mass media are mean and inhuman hordes 
that only criticize. 

</TEXT>

