<F P=100> Cambodia </F>
<H3> <TI>   Minister Plans Devaluation; Says Reserves Dwindling </TI></H3>
<F P=102>  BK1301135594 Bangkok Radio Thailand Network in Thai 1200 GMT 
13 Jan 94 </F>

<F P=103> BK1301135594 </F>
<F P=104>  Bangkok Radio Thailand Network </F>


<TEXT>
Language: <F P=105> Thai </F>
Article Type:BFN 

  [Text] A seminar on investment and the Cambodian economy 
was held at the Cambodiana Hotel this morning. At the seminar, 
Sam Rangsi, Cambodian economy and finance minister, said the 
Cambodian national budget faces constraints and financial 
reserves are dwindling. The Cambodian Government has attempted 
to undertake economic restructuring in order to become 
self-reliant. Two measures have been planned to achieve this: 
Economic policy must be continuous, laws must be transparent, 
and foreign investors must be screened; and also the Cambodian 
Government will soon devalue the riel to make the currency 
stronger. According to the Cambodian finance minister, six 
months have passed since the formation of the new Cambodian 
Government, but the economy has not yet reached a stage that 
will attract investors. The government does not have enough 
money to pay the salaries of officials. This could lead to 
demonstrations. For this reason, the Cambodian Government has 
accelerated the targeted collection of taxes to stabilize the 
country's economic position. 

</TEXT>

