<F P=100> Laos </F>
<H3> <TI>   President Thanks SRV Delegation, Views Ties </TI></H3>
<F P=102>  BK1301052794 Vientiane Vitthayou Hengsat Radio Network in 
Lao 0000 GMT 13 Jan 94 </F>

<F P=103> BK1301052794 </F>
<F P=104>  Vientiane Vitthayou Hengsat Radio Network </F>


<TEXT>
Language: <F P=105> Lao </F>
Article Type:BFN 

  [Text] Nouhak Phoumsavan, Political Bureau member of the 
Lao People's Revolutionary Party [LPRP] Central Committee and 
president of the Lao People's Democratic Republic [LPDR], 
received Vu Oanh, Politburo member, who is in charge of guiding 
mass organizations, of the Communist Party of Vietnam [CPV] 
Central Committee, and the CPV delegation at the Presidential 
Palace in Vientiane yesterday afternoon. 
  The Vu Oanh-led high-level CPV delegation is here to attend 
the funeral of Phoumi Vongvichit, adviser to the LPRP Central 
Committee, former Political Bureau member of the Party Central 
Committee, former acting president of the LPDR, former chairman 
of the Lao Front for National Construction [LFNC], and former 
deputy prime minister and minister of education, sports, and 
religion, who passed away at 0822 on 7 January. 
  Nouhak Phoumsavan expressed appreciations to the high-level 
CPV delegation led by Vu Oanh for making a trip to Laos to 
attend the funeral of Phoumi Vongvichit. This, the Lao 
president remarked, would contribute to the endlessly furthur 
improving and expanding of the long-standing special relations 
of friendship and all-around cooperation between the two 
parties, states, and peoples of Laos and Vietnam. 
  On the same occasion, Vu Oanh extended regards and deep 
regrets from the Vietnamese party, state, and people to Lao 
counterparts for the loss of Phoumi Vongvichit, a much-beloved 
leader of the party, state, and people of Laos and a good friend 
of Vietnamese people. 
  In addition, the Lao president and the guests also exchanged 
views on the issues of relations and cooperation between the 
parties, states, and peoples of Laos and Vietnam for the 
immediate future and in the long run to enhance the further 
strengthening of the time-honored fine traditions to flourish 
ever more. 

</TEXT>

