<H3> <TI>   Commentary Denounces South's Agricultural Policy </TI></H3>
<F P=102>  SK1201123394 Pyongyang KCNA in English 1049 GMT 12 Jan 94 </F>
<F P=103> SK1201123394 </F>
<F P=104>  Pyongyang KCNA </F>


<TEXT>
Language: <F P=105> English </F>
Article Type:BFN 

  [Text] Pyongyang, January 12 (KCNA) -- The South Korean 
puppets on January 8 worked out what they call "timetable for 
establishing an agricultural policy" regarding rice market 
opening and are making quite a noise as if the "committee for 
the development of rural and fishing villages" which will be 
formed by the end of this month would "increase the competitive 
power of agriculture and fisheries" and "improve living 
conditions in the rural and fishing villages." 
  Commenting on this, NODONG SINMUN today says: 
  What they are doing is a disgusting act of a political 
charlatan who causes illness and then administers medicine. 
  Since the puppets declared rice market opening, they must 
take measures to block the unrestricted flooding of American 
agricultural products such as building a higher customs barrier, 
if they want to prevent losses from it. But a "meeting of 
ministers concerned" of the puppet administration did not 
discuss such active measures but put on the order of the day 
"support" to agriculture through the collection of a new 
"special tax" and establishment of an "advisory body". What 
effect would such "measures" of the puppets have? In fact, this 
is an act to cut the lifeline of the 6 million peasants by 
market opening and kill all the people by forcing a "special 
tax" on them under the pretext of "support" to them. 
  It is impossible that the traitor Kim Yong-sam, a top- class 
flunkeyist who did not hesitate to open the rice market of South 
Korea to win the favour of his U.S. master, takes a measure to 
defend the South Korean peasants and agriculture in disregard of 
the interests of his master. 
  The Kim Yong-sam group's talk about "measures" and the like 
is aimed at creating the impression that it is concerned over 
the peasants suffering losses and thus lulling their 
ever-growing grievances and bridging over the worsening crisis 
of its rule. 

</TEXT>

