<F P=100> South Korea </F>
<H3> <TI>   North To Merge Region in Partial Economic Opening </TI></H3>
<F P=102>  SK1301090994 Seoul CHUNGANG ILBO in Korean 13 Jan 94 p 7 </F>
<F P=103> SK1301090994 </F>
<F P=104>  Seoul CHUNGANG ILBO </F>


<TEXT>
Language: <F P=105> Korean </F>
Article Type:BFN 

<F P=106> [YONHAP report from Tokyo] </F>
  [Text] The Japanese YOMIURI SHIMBUN reported on 13 January 
that North Korea is planning to merge North Hamgyong Province's 
Najin city and Sonbong County, which are close to the border 
with the PRC and Russia, and upgrade the region to a city 
directly controlled by the central government as part of its 
plan to begin full-scale work for the partial opening of its 
economy, including the construction of ports. 
  Quoting a related Seoul source, the YOMIURI SHIMBUN pointed 
out that the move to merge Najin and Sonbong is thought to 
symbolize North Korea's strategy to ease the economic 
difficulties it faces by partially opening its economy. 
  The Najin and Sonbong region is the core region of the Tumen 
River Development Plan launched by the UN Development Program. 
In December 1991, North Korea named the region a "free economic 
and trade zone," North Korea's equivalent to a special economic 
zone. 

</TEXT>

