<F P=100> South Korea </F>
<H3> <TI>   Chinese Tourists Reportedly Escape From Hotel </TI></H3>
<F P=102>  SK1301121794 Seoul YONHAP in English 1155 GMT 13 Jan 94 </F>
<F P=103> SK1301121794 </F>
<F P=104>  Seoul YONHAP </F>


<TEXT>
Language: <F P=105> English </F>
Article Type:BFN 

  [Text] Seoul, Jan. 13 (YONHAP) -- Another group of 19 
Chinese tourists, presumably all ethnic Koreans, fled their 
hotel in Seoul on Jan. 7 apparently to find jobs in the country, 
it was learned on Thursday. 
  This was seventh of such escapes involving 187 tourists from 
China since last September. 
  In the first and largest group escape, 115 Chinese 
participating in a group tour organized by the Aju Travel Co. 
fled their hotel in group on Sept. 6 last year. 
  Of the 187 who had fled, only 29 were caught in Suwon and 
forcibly flown back to China, with the whereabouts of the 
remainders having been unknown. 
  A police source said the latest 19 escapees were part of the 
24 Chinese of a group tour organized by the Tongbo Travel Co. in 
the Jilin Province, part of the ethnic Koreans' autonomous area 
in northeastern China. 
  The remaining five of the group were deported on two 
occasions by Tuesday. 
  After group escapes by Korean-Chinese were reported often 
late last year, the government has been controlling group visits 
by ethnic Koreans from China. 
  In the latest case, the 24 visitors produced passports that 
described them as ethnic Chinese and spoke Chinese only. 
  Immigration officials suspect they were in effect ethnic 
Koreans who somehow forged their papers to make themselves 
appear to be ethnic Chinese so as to get entry into Korea. 

</TEXT>

