<F P=100> South Korea </F>
<H3> <TI>   Defense Ministry Seeking `Lost' Classified Document </TI></H3>
<F P=102>  SK1301072094 Seoul YONHAP in English 0633 GMT 13 Jan 94 </F>
<F P=103> SK1301072094 </F>
<F P=104>  Seoul YONHAP </F>


<TEXT>
Language: <F P=105> English </F>
Article Type:BFN 

  [Text] Seoul, Jan. 13 (YONHAP) -- The Defense Ministry has 
lost a classified document that it sent to Rep. Cho Sun-hwan of 
the United People's Party during the National Assembly's regular 
session last year, and is trying to find it. 
  Investigators from the Defense Security Command searched the 
homes of Rep. Cho's aides -- Yi Un-chae, 38, and Chong Chu-hun, 
31 -- for the "secret" paper Thursday but came up empty handed, 
a ministry spokesman said. 
  The document contains details of the operating budget for 
the 
ministry for 1994 and could benefit Korea's enemies, he said. 
  The ministry prepared the document in September and, through 
the National Assembly Secretariat, gave a copy to each member of 
the defense and the budget and accounts committees for their 
deliberations on the defense budget. The copy sent to Cho, a 
member of the budget and accounts committee, was not returned. 
  Pressed for its return, the secretariat told the ministry in 
a letter Jan. 3 that it had no way of finding the document 
because the aide who had kept it had been fired. 
  In January 1992, Hwang In-o, the leader of a North Korean 
spy 
ring, obtained a classified Defense Ministry document through Yi 
Kun-hui, a lawmaker's secretary, and handed a photocopy to North 
Korea through Japan. 

</TEXT>

