<F P=100> Philippines </F>
<H3> <TI>   Negotiator Discusses MNLF Truce Provisions </TI></H3>
<F P=102>  BK1301054694 Manila MANILA BULLETIN in English 9 Jan 94 pp 
1, 8 </F>

<F P=103> BK1301054694 </F>
<F P=104>  Manila MANILA BULLETIN </F>


<TEXT>
Language: <F P=105> English </F>
Article Type:BFN 

<F P=106> [By Vic P. Arevalo] </F>
  [Excerpt] Zamboanga City -- A cease fire agreement between 
the government and the Moro National Liberation Front (MNLF) 
will be signed in Cotabato City today or tomorrow, depending on 
the availability of Nur Misuari, MNLF chairman who is reportedly 
still in Jolo, Sulu. 
  The joint cease fire committee, led by Marine Brig. Gen. 
Guillermo Ruiz and Maj. Gen. Abdul Sarim of the MNLF, drew up 
the agreement after three days of meeting here last 5 to 7 
January. 
  Both panels agreed that a joint cease fire monitoring office 
will be set up here to monitor, review, and evaluate violations 
of the cease fire pact. 
  Sub-monitoring offices will be set up in the 13 provinces of 
Mindanao where the cease fire is in effect. 
  Ruiz said "the ground rules of the accord will be in effect. 
The MNLF will not be allowed to recruit fighters. It will also 
be banned from training fighters during the cease fire. MNLF 
rebels will be prohibited from carrying guns outside identified 
MNLF areas." 
  He added "there will be no acts of terrorism or violence 
while the cease fire is in effect." 
  "On the other hand, government forces will not be allowed to 
conduct military operations against MNLF rebels. There will no 
naval gunfire or shelling of pinpointed rebel areas. However, 
Philippine National Police (PNP) operations against criminals 
will continue," Ruiz said. 
  If criminals hide in MNLF areas, the Armed Forces of the 
Philippines (AFP) will pursue them -- with the MNLF's help, he 
added. 
  The cease fire agreement will be signed by the joint peace 
panel represented by Manuel Yan, former ambassador to Thailand 
and AFP chief of staff, representing the government and Misuari 
for the MNLF. 
  The AFP and the PNP will provide security for Misuari when 
he 
and his group will travel to Cotabato and other provinces of 
Mindanao. [passage omitted] 

</TEXT>

</DOC>

