<F P=101> Japan </F>
<H3> <TI>   Tokyo Rejects `Quad' Talks on Market Access </TI></H3>
<F P=102>  OW1201140194 Tokyo KYODO in English 1305 GMT 12 Jan 94 </F>
<F P=103> OW1201140194 </F>
<F P=104>  Tokyo KYODO </F>


<TEXT>
Language: <F P=105> English </F>
Article Type:BFN 

  [Text] Tokyo, Jan. 12 KYODO -- Japan will not agree to a 
proposal by the United States and the European Union to hold 
talks among the so-called "Quad" countries and region on trade, 
a senior Foreign Ministry official said Wednesday [12 January]. 
  The official, who spoke on condition of anonymity, said, 
"Japan cannot agree to such an idea while they neglect to do 
what they should do and are trying to wrench something from 
Japan." 
  U.S. Trade Representative Mickey Kantor and EU Commissioner 
in charge of External Economic Affairs Leon Brittan have called 
for the opening of negotiations with their counterparts in Japan 
and Canada on market access issues. 
  The official, however, said, "it is another thing if they 
are 
willing to really seriously discuss trade rules." 

</TEXT>

