<F P=100> South Korea </F>
<H3> <TI>   Taejon, PRC City To Establish `Sisterhood Relationship' </TI></H3>
<F P=102>  SK1301005394 Seoul THE KOREA HERALD in English 13 Jan 94 p 3 </F>
<F P=103> SK1301005394 </F>
<F P=104>  Seoul THE KOREA HERALD </F>


<TEXT>
Language: <F P=105> English </F>
Article Type:BFN 

  [Text] The city of Taejon will establish a sisterhood 
relationship with Nanjing in southern China, a spokesman for the 
Taejon City Government said yesterday. 
  A five-member delegation, headed by Wang Haoliang, 
secretary- 
general of the Nanjing Municipal People's Government, will 
arrive in the Korean central city Jan. 17 for a four-day visit 
at the invitation of Taejon Mayor Yom Hong-chol, he said. 
  During their stay in Taejon, the Chinese delegates will 
discuss preparations to set up a sisterhood relationship between 
the two cities and exchange bilateral friendship memorandum. 
  They will also discuss steps to increase personnel exchanges 
and economic cooperation. They will also visit the city's 
Taedok &amp; Ginseng Corp. in Taejon, the spokesman said. 
  Nanjing, with a population of 2.47 million, is China's 
center 
stage for commercial, financial and trade activities in the 
southern region, he said. 
  The spokesman said Taejon, in accordance with the nation's 
recent emphasis on internationalization, is also seeking to set 
up sisterhood ties with other foreign cities, including Japan's 
Oda, Russia's Petersburg and Hungary's Budapest. 

</TEXT>

