<H3> <TI>   Reportage on Construction Market Access Talks </TI></H3>
<H4>   `Tough Talking' Expected </H4>
<F P=102> OW1401005094 Tokyo YOMIURI SHIMBUN in Japanese 13 Jan 94 
Morning Edition p 7--FOR OFFICIAL USE ONLY </F>

<F P=103> OW1401005094 </F>
<F P=104>  Tokyo YOMIURI SHIMBUN </F>


<TEXT>
Language: <F P=105> Japanese </F>
Article Type:BFN 

  [Text] An unofficial session of the Japan-U.S. 
construction talks started in Tokyo on 12 January. The United 
States has set 20 January as the date on which it will impose 
sanctions unless agreement is reached. With the deadline close 
at hand, the Japanese Government has sought the understanding of 
the U.S. Government by working out an action program, including 
a plan to introduce the general competitive bidding system for 
public works in April. 
  For those projects sponsored by prefectural governments that 
will be eligible for the bidding system, the Japanese Government 
has set the cost of projects at "more than about 2.3 billion 
yen." The U.S. Government, however, has demanded that this 
ceiling be lowered. 
  Moreover, although the Japanese Government intends to 
abolish 
in April the major project arrangement (MPA), which was 
exclusively worked out to help American companies, the U.S. 
Government wants it continued. It is expected there will be 
some tough talking before an accord is reached. 

</TEXT>

