<F P=100> ANNEX </F>
<F P=101> January </F>
<H3> <TI>   Reportage on Construction Market Access Talks </TI></H3>
<H4>   Accord Reportedly Reached </H4>
<F P=102> OW1401033494 Tokyo Nikkei Telecom Database in Japanese 14 
Jan 94--FOR OFFICIAL USE ONLY </F>

<F P=103> OW1401033494 </F>
<F P=104>  Tokyo Nikkei Telecom Database </F>


<TEXT>
Language: <F P=105> Japanese </F>
Article Type:BFN 

<F P=106> [From NIHON KEIZAI SHIMBUN 14 January Morning Edition] </F>
  [Text] A government source disclosed 13 January that Japan 
and the United States had basically reached an accord at the 
Japan-U.S. construction talks on Japan opening its public works 
projects to foreign countries. Agreement had been reached 
because the U.S. side had indicated it basically accepted the 
action program suggested by the Japanese side at the unofficial 
talks that started in Tokyo at the beginning of the week. 
  The action program looks to introduce a general competitive 
bidding system for large-scale public works projects beginning 
fiscal 1994. Under the program foreign companies will be 
treated on equal terms as Japanese companies. The action 
program will be officially approved by the cabinet meeting 
scheduled for 18 January. 
  The two countries have also agreed to exchange data on the 
number and cost of projects for which orders have been given to 
foreign companies, in an attempt to measure the degree of market 
opening. The U.S. Trade Representative (USTR) has indicated it 
will support the imposition of sanctions against Japan if no 
accord is reached by 20 January. However, with agreement now 
reached, it has become certain that sanctions can be avoided. 
  According to the action program agreed on by two countries 
the scale of projects to be sponsored by the central government, 
and for which the general competition bidding system will be 
introduced, will be set at more than 4.5 million SDR's (special 
drawing rights, approximately 700 million yen). 
  The level has been set at 15 million SDR's [about 2.5 
billion 
yen] for projects sponsored by local governments, including 
prefectures and special municipalities, and the 84 state-run 
corporations government, including Eastern Japan JR [Japan 
Railways], Japan Highway Public Corporation, and NTT [Nippon 
Telegraph and Telephone]. 

</TEXT>

