<F P=101> January </F>
<H3> <TI>   Ambassador to U.S. Urges Better Economic Relations </TI></H3>
<F P=102>  OW1301133694 Tokyo SANKEI SHIMBUN in Japanese 11 Jan 94 
Evening Edition p 3--FOR OFFICIAL USE ONLY </F>

<F P=103> OW1301133694 </F>
<F P=104>  Tokyo SANKEI SHIMBUN </F>


<TEXT>
Language: <F P=105> Japanese </F>
Article Type:BFN 

<F P=106> [JIJI report] </F>
  [Text] New York, 10 Jan -- At a seminar held at a hotel in 
New York City on 10 January under the auspices of JIJI, Takakazu 
Kuriyama, Japanese ambassador to the United States, said that 
Japan needs to introduce economic measures soon to successfully 
conclude the Japan-U.S. comprehensive economic talks. Moreover, 
he stressed that Japan and the United States should return their 
economic relations to a stable foundation by overcoming a sense 
of mutual distrust over such issues as an introduction of 
objective criteria and by holding constructive discussions 
within several weeks (prior to the Japanese-U.S. summit talks 
scheduled to be held in February). 
  On overall Japan-U.S. relations, the ambassador explained 
that both countries are focusing their attention only on 
economic competition and that light is not being shed on 
cooperation that both countries are carrying out in various 
areas, including aid to Russia, the peace process in Cambodia, 
and environmental issues. He said that tension exists between 
the two countries because they are unable to maintain a balance 
in their relations. He also pointed out that an important task 
is how to create a balance in their "competitive and 
cooperative" ties. 
  The ambassador then pointed out that a growing number of 
people in the United States no longer "feel that Japan poses a 
threat" and that they are becoming optimistic about Japan-U.S. 
relations thanks to noticeable changes in which the "United 
States regained confidence but Japan lost confidence" following 
the U.S. economic recovery in the past six months under the 
Clinton administration. He explained his belief that Japan-U.S. 
relations have started to change. 
  Moreover, Ambassador Kuriyama said that Japan is also to 
blame for the economic tension that exists between Japan and the 
United States. He added that he has no choice but to admit that 
Japan's insufficient structural reform during the time when the 
yen was strong created a big gap between purchasing power parity 
and the market exchange rate. 

</TEXT>

</DOC>

<DOC>
<DOCNO> FBIS3-47545 </DOCNO>
<HT>    "dreas010__a94010" </HT>


