<H3> <TI>   Official, PRC Minister Wu Discuss Yen Loan </TI></H3>
<F P=102>  OW1401103394 Tokyo MAINICHI SHIMBUN in Japanese 11 Jan 94 
Morning Edition p 9--FOR OFFICIAL USE ONLY </F>

<F P=103> OW1401103394 </F>
<F P=104>  Tokyo MAINICHI SHIMBUN </F>


<TEXT>
Language: <F P=105> Japanese </F>
Article Type:BFN 

<F P=106> [By Hidetoshi Kaneko] </F>
  [Text] Beijing, 10 Jan -- Hiroshi Hirabayashi, chief of 
the Foreign Ministry's Economic Cooperation Bureau, met with Wu 
Yi, Chinese minister of foreign economic relations and trade, on 
10 January to ask her to speed up the work of listing projects 
intended for the fourth yen loan. He also indicated five fields 
that Japan believes should be considered important in providing 
the fourth yen loan. 
  The five fields are: 1) preservation of environment; 2) 
economic infrastructure, such as transportation and 
communications; 3) city infrastructure, such as water supply and 
drainage; 4) agriculture; and 5) assistance to economically 
undeveloped areas in inland of China. The bureau chief 
expressed his hope to emphasize the northeast region among other 
regions in providing aid, saying: "We would like to place 
emphasis on the northeast region which is close to Japan." 
  Moreover, because the fourth yen loan will be the major 
focal 
point during Prime Minister Morihiro Hosokawa's visit to China 
in March -- the visit is now under coordination between Japan 
and China, Hirabayashi called on China to include "projects that 
could become a symbol of friendship between Japan and China" in 
lists of China's requests for the yen loan. Hirabayashi said 
Japan "would like to decide on projects for aid, which will be 
provided in three years, as soon as possible." 
  Minister Wu said: "China regards Japan as the largest 
partner in economic cooperation. We agree to the Japanese idea 
of emphasizing preservation of environment." 

</TEXT>

